@node Introduction "Workbench Boot Pictures Volume #2 - Introduction"

Introduction
------------

Workbench Boot Pictures are simply a collection of IFF pictures for use with 
Joseph Luk's fabulous program, `BootScreen'.  

`BootScreen' is a program which allows you to display an IFF picture while 
the hard drive is booting, much like the Microsoft Windows logo on the
IBM's.

I was influenced to draw these pictures after seeing the "rip-off" Microsoft 
Boot Pictures that were floating around and I thought the Amiga deserved
it's own exclusive Boot Screens.

So, I started work on some Boot Pictures that was exclusively "Amiga", and
related more to the Amiga OS, and I am now in my second collection of
Workbench Boot Pictures.

These pictures were drawn exclusively with Deluxe Paint IV AGA with no
touch ups done with any other programs (eg. Art Department).

This particular collection contains three pictures for the new OS 3.1,
Release 40.42, and are in 16 colours so they can be used by OCS, ECS and
AGA Amigas.

Although these pictures were designed in mind of OS 3.1 users, you may
change the OS and Release numbers to suit your own system (Please read
conditions in Copyright).

@endnode



@node Requirements "Workbench Boot Pictures Volume #2 - Requirements"

Requirements
------------

To use the pictures you will need OS 2.X+, a Hard Drive and the program
`BootScreen' written by Joseph Luk.

`BootScreen' is available on Aminet in the utils/boot directory.


@endnode



@node Installation "Workbench Boot Pictures Volume #2 - Installation"

Installation
------------

Firstly, if you have not done so already, you will need to install
`BootScreen', follow the instructions accompanied with the program
relating to how to install it.
 
After extracting the WB_BootPics2.lha file, you will see a number of .IFF 
files, choose the pictures you want and copy them to your Presets directory 
in your SYS: partition.  You can do this from the CLI by typing;



     copy <path containing WB_BootPics2 directory> SYS:Prefs/Presets


Or alternatively using a Disk Management Program Like Directory Opus.

After copying these files, load the BootScreen Prefs program in the Prefs 
directory of your SYS: partition and choose the filename you copied.  Now
BootScreen will use that picture everytime it boots up!   

@endnode



